<p>Operationalising Design in Traveloka Context</p>

<p>An excerpt from The Time to Operate is Now! (by Meredith Black) And Introduction to Design Ops (by Dave Malouf). Main point: Convince the design team about the structure of new DesignOps in Traveloka. And what the team can do.</p>

<p>“What should designers do?” Is a simple question which answer is not always easy. Designer’s role can be different from one company to another, depend on many factors such as organisation structure and business challenges to name a few.</p>

<p>It’s only natural to ask around “what should designers do?”, especially if you are a team of one person in a company that recently exploring value of design. Questions like “should designers code?” reflect the state of many design organisation, especially in digital start up company.</p>

<p>Fast forward, when a company is entering hyper-growth mode. Every department tend to grow and scale as well, and design department is no exception — like in Traveloka.</p>

<p>Along with the scale, scope of works becoming increasingly complex. More people brought in, jobs are broken down. Roles start to handle specialised responsibilities — often in the absence of clear cut boundaries. Good collaboration is no longer optional.</p>

<p>Hyper-growth sometimes feels like sweeping a bunch of leaves on the road in autumn. Firefighting is the norm around. Without realising, it feels too many things to do! [gasp].</p>

<p>Back then, designers used to handle everything “design”. We were comfortable working with little to no process, undocumented design decisions, and it’s finally catching up to us. While navigating the role specialisation, we still think some works are normal and necessary as part of our daily to-dos. If we’re not careful, these “other than design” works can creep up and eating our time away.</p>

<p>Understanding DesignOps
Understanding DesignOps can be tricky. It’s new, borrowed from mature role in software development called DevOps. From the outset, it seems just like another design role.</p>

<p>Similar to design roles that can be different in each company, DesignOps also called differently in different companies. Some call it Design Program Managers, Project Coordinator, Chief of Staff, Research Ops, Research Coordinator, Product Design Producer (borrowing from movie-making producers), and Design Ops.</p>

<p>The point is, design organisation everywhere might experience similar problem in growing and scaling, but there is no silver bullet. It’s really important to put designOps in context.</p>

<p>According to Dave Malouf, Design Ops is Everything that supports high quality crafts, methods, and processes (in context of design). Basically anything to keep designers focus on designing.</p>

<p>What should we focus on instead? Whatever your title is, in general designers should focus on designing:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Understanding problem in context, from multiple perspectives.</li>
  <li>Facilitate solving those problems through series of activites.</li>
  <li>Take into account branches of consideration.</li>
  <li>Form an intention.</li>
  <li>Rendering those intentions.</li>
  <li>Making sure the intentions are conveyed to the users.</li>
</ul>

<p>What is designOps? DesignOps is team inside design department that will take care the operational aspect of design.</p>

<p>But in daily activities, we as designers often doing things that is not designing.</p>

<p>We are not aiming to be the bottleneck, obvioiusly. We are trying to making process transparent and help you walk through it. With transparency we can manage expectation, with expecation managed we can build comfort and trust in the end. This always be our goals from the start.</p>

<p>What is operation? Series of functions and tasks that are involved in a single process. For example, a manufacturing operation.
So it will help designers in design team with repeat-able procedure and practice that can be performed to achieve expected outputs.</p>

<p>Scopes of Ops
Operating in context
There is no silver bullet.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Workflow: how the design work flows within the company</li>
  <li>Tools: what they need to get the job done</li>
  <li>Governance: who needs to see the work, and when</li>
  <li>Infrastructure: what the team needs to work more efficiently</li>
  <li>Budget: how much running that team costs, and why</li>
  <li>Headcount: how many people are needed, with which skills</li>
  <li>Pipeline: projects coming up and how well staffed the team is</li>
  <li>Retention: how to make people want to stay</li>
  <li>Education: what skills are missing and how to learn them</li>
  <li>Evangelization: help the org understand the value of design</li>
  <li>According to Meredith Black from Pinterest, key areas for DesignOps are:
    <ul>
      <li>Design process</li>
      <li>Build relationships</li>
      <li>Provide visibility</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Drive operations</li>
</ul>

<p>Anything to keep designers focus on designing. The purpose of DesignOps is to keep designers focused on designing.</p>

<p>To empower designer to focus on work that matters and collaborate confidently</p>

<p>Again, it’s very important to put operation in context. To be extremely honest, there is no one single correct solution for DesignOps out there.
We are only facing similar problems in different context of company.
Some company like Pinterest apply resourcing, program management, team onboarding, and Team morale and education,
While others divide it into: Process, People, Priorities.
Other model is from Courtney Kaplan (Director of Design Program Manager at Facebook):</p>

<ul>
  <li>Operation Health of design team through data</li>
  <li>Program Onboarding, education, inspiration</li>
  <li>Product (partner with product) Teamwork, key initiatives, tools &amp; standards</li>
</ul>

<p>ThoughtBox: What is our DesignOps Model?
Through those examples alone, it’s obvious that DesignOps can be very different in each organization.</p>

<p>The signs of design ops needs
(You tell me if we do have these symptomps)</p>

<ul>
  <li>Specialization of role. Design roles in the company are getting specific, no more “fullstack designer”. This resulting in higher need of clearer collaboration model.</li>
  <li>Hard to keep everyone in sync resulting in communication gap</li>
  <li>Designers just give up and say just tell me what to do Safe haven, synptomp</li>
  <li>Constant Changes risk of duplicating works</li>
  <li>Scaling up</li>
</ul>

