  <li>Regular Feedback Session</li>
  <li>Designer’s All Hands</li>
</ol>

<p>Facilitation</p>

<ol>
  <li>Facilitate alignment, for example sync with design leads</li>
  <li>Build external relationship</li>
  <li>Build cross-functional relationship</li>
</ol>

<p>People Growth</p>

<ul>
  <li>Alignment (of expectation/workflow)</li>
</ul>

<p>Wait, WHY DesignOps?
Don’t we have CDC? Exactly akan ada banyak intersection antara CDC dan DesignOps. You may even think about DesignOps as executive extension from CDC.
bisa di-expect ngapain aja?
How to start?</p>

<ul>
  <li>Go slow what are our quick wins</li>
  <li>Start small: meeting notes, documenting culture, Weekly Visual status</li>
  <li>Don’t force process</li>
  <li>Don’t tell people what to do :)</li>
</ul>

<p>Quick wins</p>

<ul>
  <li>Efficient onboardings</li>
  <li>education program</li>
  <li>new design tools &amp; license management (how do we assess this)</li>
  <li>Audience building for research</li>
</ul>

<p>ThoughtBox what are our Quick wins as design ops?</p>

<p>How do we know if design ops is succesful:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Teams will be better organized</li>
  <li>Leadership will gain a better understanding of what makes their teams tick</li>
  <li>Cross-functional teams will have more visibility into—and a better understanding of—the design process. No more blackbox (design demistified, design is not magic)</li>
  <li>Do you know what are the design team working on?</li>
  <li>By making design process more transparent, trust will be built</li>
  <li>Manage resourcing, drive the day-to-day project flows, , support team health, and basically facilitate anything that allows creative teams to focus on what they do best</li>
  <li>Team health is the kpi?
DesignOps in Traveloka?
posisinya dia in a grander scheme of structure.
    <ol>
      <li>Identify needs</li>
      <li>Define roles, responsibilities, scope</li>
      <li>Determine orbiting roles</li>
    </ol>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>DEFINING DESIGN OPS IN TRAVELOKA CAN TRY USING THE CANVAS
Conversation starter for DesignOps:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Do you have visibility into what the design team is working on?</li>
  <li>Do you know if the team is working well cross-functionally with product and engineering colleagues?</li>
  <li>Does the team have clear and actionable goals they are driving toward, and are they meeting them?</li>
  <li>Are there regular design critiques or feedback sessions?</li>
  <li>Are the product manager, engineer, and designer aligned with what’s shipping?</li>
  <li>Is the team meeting deadlines?</li>
</ul>

<p>From DesignOps Canvas by Dave Malouf, Abby Covert, Kristin Skinner, Lou Rosenfeld, Dave Mastronardi
What do we do?</p>

<ul>
  <li>What is the value we provide?</li>
  <li>What does “good” look like?</li>
  <li>What is our process &amp; or operating rhythm?</li>
  <li>What methods and tools do we use?</li>
  <li>What are our inputs &amp; outputs?</li>
  <li>How do we work together?</li>
</ul>

<p>Who are we?
Teammates</p>

<ul>
  <li>Who are we looking for?</li>
  <li>How do we recruit people?</li>
  <li>How do we develop our people?</li>
  <li>How do we retain people?</li>
</ul>

<p>Stakeholders</p>

<ul>
  <li>Who are our most valuable partners?</li>
  <li>What makes them successful?</li>
  <li>What obstacles stand in their way?</li>
  <li>How do we work with them?</li>
</ul>

<p>Support</p>

<ul>
  <li>What support and resources do we need?</li>
</ul>

<p>How do we communicate</p>

<ul>
  <li>Internally within our teams?</li>
  <li>externally with other stakeholders?</li>
  <li>How we educate &amp; evangelize design?</li>
  <li>How do we give and get feedback?</li>
  <li>How do we share our knowledge and new learnings?</li>
</ul>

<p>What constrains us</p>

<ul>
  <li>What regulatory, security, or other realities constrain what is possible?</li>
  <li>How do we manage conflicts &amp; tradeoffs?</li>
  <li>How do we manage risk?</li>
</ul>

<p>How are we structured</p>

<ul>
  <li>How do we balance autonomy &amp; the common good?</li>
  <li>(autonomy being the freedom and independence we need to do great work)</li>
  <li>(common good being the things we need to do consistently in order to work well together)</li>
</ul>

<p>Management</p>

<ul>
  <li>What is our mission?</li>
  <li>How do we set goals?</li>
  <li>How do we track and measure success?</li>
  <li>How are we structured?</li>
  <li>Who is responsible for what?</li>
</ul>

<p>What else should we be thinking about?
Setting up Design Ops team for success
*</p>

<p>manage communications and coordination across all teams and projects.
Establish structure
ensure consistent quality at scale. DesignOps is uniquely adept at defining, socializing, and maintaining these type of workflows.
Burnout hustle zen
Creative teams are uniquely vulnerable to the subjective nature of their work. On any given project, they might receive bad feedback, late feedback, conflicting feedback, and even feedback from unknown parties with no apparent involvement in a project.
managing contracts—setting the scope of work, negotiating rates and terms, coordinating with the finance team—is absolutely crucial for team success. A DesignOps function can manage this responsibility, giving both the design team and external resources an informed and helpful point of contact
Understand every single design process and every role contribution to it
areas include design tooling and systems,, team development, and budgeting.</p>

<p>Conclusion
DesignOps gak bisa kerja sendiri. Please help them help you</p>
